    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-12T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-12T12:00:00-05:00" n="824"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d824">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.6176/7–1244: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-12T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 12, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 2—3:06 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5490. Reference Embassy’s 5103.<note n="34" xml:id="d824fn34">Telegram of June
                        28, 5 p.m., not printed.</note> Complete British representation still
                    undecided. However unofficially understand following seven <pb facs="0983"
                        n="973" xml:id="pg_973"/> delegates, Franks, Chairman, Clauson, Fennelly,
                        Beharrell,<note n="35" xml:id="d824fn35">Sir George Beharrell, Chairman,
                        Dunlop Rubber Company.</note> Hay, Figg, one unnamed [from] Foreign Office
                    plus four advisers, Bail-lieu,<note n="36" xml:id="d824fn36">Sir Clive L.
                        Baillieu, Director, Dunlop Rubber Company; Head of British Raw Materials
                        Mission at Washington, 1942–1943.</note> and one each unnamed from
                    following: Board of Trade, Treasury, Industry, plus Secretariat Hall,<note
                        n="37" xml:id="d824fn37">R. L. Hall, Assistant Secretary, British Ministry
                        of Supply.</note> A. G. Pawson.<note n="38" xml:id="d824fn38">A. G. Pawson,
                        British Colonial Office.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[A press release issued by the Department of State on July 18, 1944,
                        announced the Department’s acceptance of the British invitation to engage in
                        conversations on postwar rubber problems and listed the advisers who would
                        accompany Mr. Lockwood and Mr. Phillips to London; for text of press
                        release, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 23,
                        1944, page 84.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
